WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.160
 Now I'm gonna talk a little bit about Object Lifecycle.

00:00:02.160 --> 00:00:05.360
 And what we mean by Object Lifecycle is the act of creating

00:00:05.360 --> 00:00:06.480
 and destroying these objects.

00:00:06.480 --> 00:00:09.880
 And I've been using this term constructor already.

00:00:09.880 --> 00:00:13.960
 And so when we declare a variable, whether it's a string

00:00:13.960 --> 00:00:16.680
 or a dictionary or a party animal, whether we create them

00:00:16.680 --> 00:00:19.280
 and then they're discarded, and there's all this dynamic

00:00:19.280 --> 00:00:23.560
 memory that comes and goes, and we as the writers of objects

00:00:23.560 --> 00:00:26.860
 have the ability to insert ourselves at the moment

00:00:26.860 --> 00:00:29.960
 of object creation and at the moment of object destruction.

00:00:29.960 --> 00:00:33.780
 And we make special functions that we call the constructor,

00:00:33.780 --> 00:00:36.360
 the object constructor, or the class constructor,

00:00:36.360 --> 00:00:37.600
 and the destructor.

00:00:37.600 --> 00:00:40.200
 And we don't actually explicitly call them.

00:00:40.200 --> 00:00:44.680
 They're called automatically by Python on our behalf.

00:00:44.680 --> 00:00:47.880
 And so the constructor is much more commonly used.

00:00:47.880 --> 00:00:50.600
 It's used to set up any initial values of variables

00:00:50.600 --> 00:00:52.720
 if necessary, et cetera, et cetera.

00:00:52.720 --> 00:00:58.880
 Destructors, we'll cover them, but they're used very rarely.

00:00:58.880 --> 00:01:01.000
 So here's a bit of code that we've got.

00:01:01.000 --> 00:01:02.440
 It's our party animal, and a lot of it

00:01:02.440 --> 00:01:05.920
 is the same as what we've been doing so far.

00:01:05.920 --> 00:01:08.680
 So we have this variable x, and the constructor

00:01:08.680 --> 00:01:12.680
 has a special name, underscore, underscore, init, underscore.

00:01:12.680 --> 00:01:16.360
 Again, we pass in the instance of the object, self.

00:01:16.360 --> 00:01:18.440
 And in this one, all we're going to do is print out

00:01:18.440 --> 00:01:20.000
 that you're constructed.

00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:21.920
 And here's this code that we've had before.

00:01:21.920 --> 00:01:24.120
 And now we have underscore, underscore, del,

00:01:24.120 --> 00:01:25.560
 and then we pass in self.

00:01:25.560 --> 00:01:28.280
 And we'll just print out that we're being destructed

00:01:28.280 --> 00:01:31.040
 and what the current value of x is

00:01:31.040 --> 00:01:32.720
 for that particular instance.

00:01:32.720 --> 00:01:38.080
 So let's go ahead and run this.

00:01:38.080 --> 00:01:40.160
 This is the constructing of it.

00:01:40.160 --> 00:01:43.120
 And so in this case, this line right here

00:01:43.120 --> 00:01:46.360
 is causing the I am constructed message to come out.

00:01:46.360 --> 00:01:52.200
 Then we do an party, an party, and that says one and two.

00:01:52.200 --> 00:01:53.540
 And here's an interesting thing.

00:01:53.540 --> 00:01:55.920
 We're actually going to destroy this variable

00:01:55.920 --> 00:02:00.560
 by throwing away an no longer points at that object.

00:02:00.560 --> 00:02:02.040
 An's going to point to 42.

00:02:02.040 --> 00:02:05.120
 So we're going to sort of overwrite an and put 42 in it.

00:02:05.120 --> 00:02:08.680
 And at that point, Python's like, oh, this whole little object

00:02:08.680 --> 00:02:11.640
 that I just created, somewhere it's out here,

00:02:11.640 --> 00:02:15.080
 it's vaporizing it and throwing it away.

00:02:15.080 --> 00:02:17.840
 And so before this line completes,

00:02:17.840 --> 00:02:20.760
 it actually calls our destructor on our behalf.

00:02:20.760 --> 00:02:22.520
 And so that message comes out.

00:02:22.520 --> 00:02:26.000
 So we are allowed, as the builder of these objects,

00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:28.440
 to add these little chunks of code that says,

00:02:28.440 --> 00:02:31.240
 I want to be involved at the moment this object is created

00:02:31.240 --> 00:02:33.920
 and I want to be involved at the moment that this object is

00:02:33.920 --> 00:02:34.960
 destroyed.

00:02:34.960 --> 00:02:39.200
 Now, in this last line, an is no longer a party animal.

00:02:39.200 --> 00:02:41.680
 An is now an integer.

00:02:41.680 --> 00:02:42.900
 It's got a 42 in it.

00:02:42.900 --> 00:02:43.560
 It's gone.

00:02:43.560 --> 00:02:44.520
 It's been created.

00:02:44.520 --> 00:02:45.120
 It was used.

00:02:45.120 --> 00:02:47.000
 And then it was destroyed.

00:02:47.000 --> 00:02:49.240
 So you've got to be careful if you overwrite something.

00:02:49.240 --> 00:02:52.680
 You've got to sort of throw the object away.

00:02:52.680 --> 00:02:55.680
 So the constructor is a special block of code

00:02:55.680 --> 00:02:58.840
 that's called when the object is created to set the object up.

00:02:58.840 --> 00:03:03.400
 So we can create lots of instances.

00:03:03.400 --> 00:03:06.120
 Everything we've done so far is we make a class

00:03:06.120 --> 00:03:09.080
 and then we create one instance, one object.

00:03:09.080 --> 00:03:11.200
 And each of these objects ends up

00:03:11.200 --> 00:03:12.560
 being stored in its own variable.

00:03:12.560 --> 00:03:14.520
 We have a variable an and we've been using it.

00:03:14.520 --> 00:03:16.200
 But the more interesting thing begins

00:03:16.200 --> 00:03:18.760
 to happen when we have multiple instances

00:03:18.760 --> 00:03:21.880
 of the same class sitting in different variables.

00:03:21.880 --> 00:03:24.640
 And it has its own copy of the instance variables.

00:03:24.640 --> 00:03:27.040
 So let's take a look at this.

00:03:27.040 --> 00:03:32.880
 So this code here, I've taken out the destructor.

00:03:32.880 --> 00:03:35.000
 And it shows a little bit more information.

00:03:35.000 --> 00:03:37.080
 So now we're going to put two variables in here.

00:03:37.080 --> 00:03:40.440
 We're going to have a current score or whatever and a name.

00:03:40.440 --> 00:03:43.720
 And this time, we're going to add a parameter

00:03:43.720 --> 00:03:45.080
 onto the constructor.

00:03:45.080 --> 00:03:48.120
 And so the self comes in sort of automatically

00:03:48.120 --> 00:03:50.120
 as the object is being constructed.

00:03:50.120 --> 00:03:53.240
 But if we put a parameter on the constructor call, which

00:03:53.240 --> 00:03:58.280
 is this party animal call, then this comes in as the z variable.

00:03:58.280 --> 00:04:00.760
 And so self is the object itself.

00:04:00.760 --> 00:04:04.320
 And z, this first parameter, is whatever parameter we put here.

00:04:04.320 --> 00:04:06.560
 Everything we've done so far has no parameter here.

00:04:06.560 --> 00:04:08.280
 But now we have a parameter here.

00:04:08.280 --> 00:04:11.960
 And then that means that when we call this constructor,

00:04:11.960 --> 00:04:14.800
 name is going to be Sally in this particular thing.

00:04:14.800 --> 00:04:16.680
 And then I'll say, oh, self.name,

00:04:16.680 --> 00:04:18.800
 which will be Sally has been constructed.

00:04:18.800 --> 00:04:21.200
 And so then we have this.

00:04:21.200 --> 00:04:23.480
 And that object is now constructed.

00:04:23.480 --> 00:04:25.640
 And then we put it in the variable s.

00:04:25.640 --> 00:04:27.480
 And then we call the party method on that.

00:04:27.480 --> 00:04:28.800
 And we construct a different one.

00:04:28.800 --> 00:04:30.280
 And so this time, it calls.

00:04:30.280 --> 00:04:32.880
 And z is Jim.

00:04:32.880 --> 00:04:37.320
 And we basically have another copy of this.

00:04:37.320 --> 00:04:40.280
 As it runs down here, when this is called,

00:04:40.280 --> 00:04:44.920
 it makes one instance and stores that in the variable s.

00:04:44.920 --> 00:04:46.600
 And there's a variable x in there.

00:04:46.600 --> 00:04:47.600
 There's a name in there.

00:04:47.600 --> 00:04:49.200
 There's an init method in party.

00:04:49.200 --> 00:04:50.360
 And that's all in here.

00:04:50.360 --> 00:04:51.680
 All that stuff is in here.

00:04:51.680 --> 00:04:53.760
 And now we say, let's make-- and that's

00:04:53.760 --> 00:04:57.000
 going to have Sally in there.

00:04:57.000 --> 00:04:59.240
 On s.party, then this turns into a one.

00:04:59.240 --> 00:05:01.080
 Then we're going to do another constructor.

00:05:01.080 --> 00:05:02.880
 And so it's going to make a whole new thing.

00:05:02.880 --> 00:05:04.560
 And it's going to store that in j.

00:05:04.560 --> 00:05:06.160
 And this one's going to have Jim in it.

00:05:06.160 --> 00:05:08.960
 And then we're going to call j.party.

00:05:08.960 --> 00:05:10.440
 That turns that into a one.

00:05:10.440 --> 00:05:13.800
 And then s.party will cause this to be a two.

00:05:13.800 --> 00:05:18.480
 And so what happens is we have now two objects, one

00:05:18.480 --> 00:05:21.000
 in the variable s and one in the variable j.

00:05:21.000 --> 00:05:23.760
 And they have separate copies of their instance variables.

00:05:23.760 --> 00:05:27.000
 These are the instance variables or the object fields

00:05:27.000 --> 00:05:27.520
 or whatever.

00:05:27.520 --> 00:05:28.760
 But they're the variables.

00:05:28.760 --> 00:05:32.400
 But the key is that every time we do a new construction,

00:05:32.400 --> 00:05:34.000
 it duplicates this.

00:05:34.000 --> 00:05:35.560
 And there's another copy of it.

00:05:35.560 --> 00:05:37.440
 So there's an x within s.

00:05:37.440 --> 00:05:46.360
 So s.x is this variable, and j.x is that variable.

00:05:46.360 --> 00:05:48.680
 So the next thing we'll talk about is inheritance.

00:05:48.680 --> 00:05:51.640
 And that's the idea of taking one class

00:05:51.640 --> 00:05:53.480
 and extending it to make something new.

00:06:07.440 --> 00:06:10.020
 (upbeat music)

